#, no-wrap
msgid "Conditional structures"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the `$?` variable is used to know the result of a test or the execution of a command, it can only be displayed and has no effect on the execution of a script.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:36
#, no-wrap
msgid "But we can use it in a condition.\n"
"**If** the test is good **then** I do this action **otherwise** I do this other action.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid "Syntax of the conditional alternative `if`:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "if command\n"
"then\n"
"    command if $?=0\n"
"else\n"
"    command if $?!=0\n"
"fi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:50
#, no-wrap
msgid "The command placed after the word `if` can be any command since it is its return code (`$?`) that will be evaluated.\n"
"It is often convenient to use the `test` command to define several actions depending on the result of this test (file exists, variable not empty, write rights set).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:52
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using a classical command (`mkdir`, `tar`, ...) allows you to define the actions to be performed in case of success, or the error messages to be displayed in case of failure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "if [[ -e /etc/passwd ]]\n"
"then\n"
"    echo \"The file exists\"\n"
"else\n"
"    echo \"The file does not exist\"\n"
"fi\n\n"
"if mkdir rep\n"
"then\n"
"    cd rep\n"
"fi\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the `else` block starts with a new `if` structure, you can merge the `else` and `if` with `elif` as shown below:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "[...]\n"
"else\n"
"  if [[ -e /etc/ ]]\n"
"[...]\n\n"
"[...]\n"
"# is equivalent to\n"
"elif [[ -e /etc ]]\n"
"[...]\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "!!! Note \"Summary\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:86
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The structure `if` / `then` / `else` / `fi` evaluates the command placed after if:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the return code of this command is `0` (`true`) the shell will execute the commands placed after `then`;\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '    * '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "If the return code is different from `0` (`false`) the shell will execute the commands placed after `else`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The `else` block is optional.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "    There is often a need to perform some actions only if the evaluation of the command is true and to do nothing if it is false.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "    The word `fi` closes the structure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "When there is only one command to execute in the `then` block, it is possible to use a simpler syntax.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/06-conditional-structures.md:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "The command to execute if `$?` is `true` is placed after `&&` while the command to execute if `$?` is `false` is placed after `||` (optional).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
